**Scenario :**
- You are given a working **Spring Boot API** that stores **task titles**.
The API works correctly, but it is written using an **all-in-one controller**, which is **not a good design**.

---

**Instructions:**
1. **Complete your code** first.
2. Click on **"Run"** to **start the server** and make sure it runs correctly.
3. If you **make any changes** to the code after running, you must **run the server again**.
4. Only after running the server with the **latest changes**, your submission will reflect the updated solution.
5. **Do not submit** if the server is not running; otherwise, your solution will **fail**.



---

**Goal** \
Convert this into Layered Architecture by separating responsibilities and cleaning up the code.

**API Details :** (Already Working)
- `POST /api/tasks` → Add a task title
- `GET /api/tasks/list` → Get all task titles

**Look at the given `TaskController` code in your IDE and run the code.**
- The controller is already working
- It handles request mapping
- It stores task titles and logic together
- This code does **NOT** follow **Layered Architecture**.

---

**Your Task** \
Refactor the existing code into a proper layered architecture by following below rules:
- Do NOT change API URLs
- Do NOT change response messages
- Use in-memory storage only
- Follow this flow strictly:
```sss
Controller → Service → Repository
```
---

**Now Follow These Steps Carefully**

**Step 1: Create Repository Folder & File**
- Go to this path:
`src/main/java/com/example/demo`
- Create a new folder : `repository`
- Inside repository, create a file `TaskRepository.java`
- **Add this code:**
```java
package com.example.demo.repository;

import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;

@Repository
public class TaskRepository {

    private final List tasks = new ArrayList<>();

    public void save(String title) {
        tasks.add(title);
    }

    public List findAll() {
        return tasks;
    }
}
```


**Step 2: Create Service Folder & File**
- Go to the same base path:
`src/main/java/com/example/demo`
- Create a new folder : `service`
- Inside service, create a file : `TaskService.java`
- **Add this code:**
```java
package com.example.demo.service;

import com.example.demo.repository.TaskRepository;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Service;
import java.util.List;

@Service
public class TaskService {

    private final TaskRepository taskRepository;

    public TaskService(TaskRepository taskRepository) {
        this.taskRepository = taskRepository;
    }

    public void addTask(String title) {
        taskRepository.save(title);
    }

    public List getAllTasks() {
        return taskRepository.findAll();
    }
}
```

**Step 3: Update Existing Controller**
- Open this file:
```sss
src/main/java/com/example/demo/controller/TaskController.java
```

**Make These Changes**
- Remove any List used for storage
- Remove task logic
- Inject `TaskService`

**Updated `TaskController.java`:**
```java
package com.example.demo.controller;

import com.example.demo.service.TaskService;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;
import java.util.List;

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/tasks")
public class TaskController {

    private final TaskService taskService;

    public TaskController(TaskService taskService) {
        this.taskService = taskService;
    }

    @PostMapping
    public String addTask(@RequestBody String title) {
        taskService.addTask(title);
        return "Task added successfully!";
    }

    @GetMapping("/list")
    public List getTasks() {
        return taskService.getAllTasks();
    }
}
```

**Final Folder Structure (After Refactoring)**
```sss
src/main/java/com/example/demo
├── DemoApplication.java
├── controller
│   └── TaskController.java
├── repository
│   └── TaskRepository.java
└── service
    └── TaskService.java
```

---

**Test the APIs** \
After completing all the steps, **run the application**. \
Now test both endpoints to make sure everything still works.

**Test 1: Add a Task (POST)**
- Method: `POST`
- URL: `/api/tasks`
- Body: \
Send a plain text task title, for example: `Learn Spring Boot`


**Expected Output**: 
```sss
Task added successfully!
```

**Test 2: Get All Tasks (GET)**
- Method: GET
- URL: /api/tasks/list

**Expected Output:** 
```sss
["Learn Spring Boot"]
```

---

In this practice, you **refactored an already working application**. \
You converted a **single-controller (all-in-one) code** into a proper **Layered Architecture**. \
Earlier, the controller was handling everything — request handling, logic, and data storage — all in one place.  
Now, responsibilities are separated into different layers, making the code cleaner and easier to maintain.

**What’s Next?** \
In the next topic, you will understand how layered architecture works internally. \
You will learn:
- How Controller, Service, and Repository communicate with each other
- How Spring automatically connects these layers
- How the request flows through the application step by step

Now that you have structured the code correctly, it’s time to understand how the layered architecture actually works

